#  PROBLEM: How does a computer "understand" text like a human?
#
#  ── APPROACH 1 (Old/Bad): Bag-of-Words / TF-IDF ──────────────────────────
#  Imagine giving each unique word in your game's vocabulary a slot in a giant
#  checkbox list. The sentence "I want to buy a scroll" becomes a list of
#  10,000 checkboxes: most are False (0), a few are True (1).
#
#  ✗ "buy" and "purchase" have ZERO relationship — they're just two different
#    checkboxes. The model has no idea they mean the same thing.
#  ✗ The list is enormous (10,000+ numbers) but almost all are zero. Wasteful.
#  ✗ Word ORDER is lost. "The scroll ate the wizard" = "The wizard ate the scroll"
#
#  ── APPROACH 2 (Our Approach): Word Embeddings ───────────────────────────
#  Instead of a checkbox, every word gets a small list of floating-point
#  numbers — its "coordinates" in a semantic space. Think of it like a map:
#
#      "buy"      → [0.82, -0.11,  0.44, ...]   (32 numbers)
#      "purchase" → [0.79, -0.08,  0.41, ...]   (32 numbers, VERY SIMILAR!)
#      "dragon"   → [-0.9,  0.55, -0.22, ...]   (32 numbers, very different)
#
#  Words with similar MEANINGS end up with similar coordinates. The model
#  learns these coordinates automatically during training. This is done via
#  PyTorch's nn.Embedding layer — a simple lookup table that is trained
#  alongside the rest of the network.
#
#  ✓ "buy" ≈ "purchase" ≈ "acquire"  (close in embedding space)
#  ✓ Compact: 32 numbers per word, not 10,000
#  ✓ The model learns CONTEXT from the sequence of embeddings
#
#  ── THE PIPELINE (End-to-End) ────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#  Player types:  "Are you trying to rob me blind?"
